# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] The book was reviewed in contemporary periodicals including the *London Medical Gazette*, *The Athenaeum*, and *The Veterinary Record*.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] It was later noted by writers including Henry S.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Ralph Fletcher (1780—1851) was a surgeon based in Gloucester.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He studied at St Bartholomew's Hospital in London and received an M.D. from the University of Edinburgh Medical School.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He held appointments at the Gloucester Infirmary, Dispensary, and Lunatic Asylum.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He published medical papers on the relation between mental and physical health.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Fletcher was twice elected Mayor of Gloucester and served as president of the local branch of the Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals in Gloucester.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He lived on Barton Street, near the city's animal pound, and his observations of the animals kept there were said to have inspired *A Few Notes on Cruelty to Animals*.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] In a brief "Preliminary Note", Fletcher writes about the suffering of animals, especially those dependent on humans.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He rejects the view that animals are insensible to pain or that their suffering is divinely ordained, and argues for compassion on moral and theological grounds.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] In "Importance of the Subject", Fletcher draws on his experience as president of the Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals in Gloucester.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He writes that public acts of cruelty form only a small part of a wider problem, and that abuse often takes place in private spaces such as stables, slaughterhouses, and homes.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He argues that existing legislation was inadequate, because small fines and judicial discretion to reduce sentences did not deter offenders.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] The main part of the book consists of notes on individual animals and practices.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Fletcher describes donkeys as animals commonly subjected to overwork and neglect.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He condemns blood sports such as shooting tied cocks and badger-baiting.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] His discussion of cats and dogs contrasts their treatment: he writes that cats were often tormented or killed for amusement, while dogs suffered from starvation, beatings, cart-work, and fighting.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Fletcher criticises methods used in the rearing and slaughter of calves and lambs, including starvation and repeated bleeding to produce white veal.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He writes about overwork, neglect, and abandonment, and argues that owners as well as drivers should be held legally responsible.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Fletcher ends by calling for tougher penalties for cruelty, official oversight of slaughterhouses and stables, wider public instruction in humane treatment, and hospitals for sick and injured animals.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] A review in the *London Medical Gazette* described the book as the work of a hospital surgeon acquainted with suffering.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] The reviewer agreed with Fletcher's criticism of animal experimentation, but called his proposal for hospitals for animals a "somewhat Utopian scheme" said to have some precedent in the East.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Salt in the "Bibliography of Animal Rights" section of his 1892 work *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress*, where he referred to it as a treatise on animal cruelty.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] In his 1989 reference work *Keyguide to Information Sources in Animal Rights*, Charles R.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Magel described *A Few Notes on Cruelty to Animals* as an early account of animal abuse in the Gloucester area and noted its proposal for hospitals for animals modelled on human institutions.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/abandoned-pets] Animal welfare laws in many states of the United States make it a crime to abandon a pet.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/abandoned-pets] Often, when abandoned, pets are forced to fend for themselves and become stray or feral.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/abandoned-pets] Feral cats are said to outnumber feral dogs and can become challenging to handle and socialize enough to be re-introduced to a new human owner.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/abandoned-pets] In general, only some newly abandoned cats and very young feral kittens can be tamed.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/abandoned-pets] There is a necessity to investigate interventions to prevent companion-animal relinquishment.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/abandoned-pets] Stray animals increase potential exposure to zoonotic diseases like rabies.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/abandoned-pets] Cat bites or scratches involving stray or feral animals are eight times more common than dog bites.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/abandoned-pets] The impacts of dog and cat predation on wildlife can also be significant.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/abandoned-pets] Some pets relinquished to an animal shelter will be euthanized due to a lack of space or financial resources.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/abandoned-pets] Millions of companion animals enter animal shelters every year in the United States.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/abandoned-pets] However, the number of dogs and cats euthanized in US shelters declined from approximately 2.6 million in 2011 to 1.5 million in 2018.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/abandoned-pets] This decline can be partially explained by an increase in the percentage of animals adopted, and an increase in the number of stray animals successfully returned to their owners.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/abandoned-pets] Studies show that the majority of people who relinquish an animal also report being emotionally attached to the animal.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/abandoned-pets] It has been reported that when forced to abandon their animals in an evacuation, people suffer mental issues such as grief, depression, and post-traumatic stress disorder.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/abandoned-pets] Recognizing the importance of pets to their owners and their role in public health is an essential first step in improving a public health problem that has been seen repeatedly in the past and is unlikely to change in the future.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/abandoned-pets] Pet abandonment increased during the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/abandoned-pets] In early 2009, the ASPCA published advice for people facing foreclosure and the loss of their pets, recommending finding a foster or adoption situation for your pet, being aware of rental property rules for pets, and checking with animal shelters and animal rescue groups.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-education-society] The **American Humane Education Society** (**AHES**) was an American organization founded in 1889 by George T.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-education-society] Angell in Boston, Massachusetts, to promote humane education.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-education-society] It worked with the Massachusetts Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals (MSPCA), and *Our Dumb Animals* served as an official publication of both organizations.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-education-society] The society was merged into the MSPCA in 2010.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-education-society] Angell (1823–1909) founded the AHES in 1889 with the stated aim of carrying "unsectarian humane education" beyond Massachusetts and supporting the creation of Bands of Mercy and other humane societies.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-education-society] The society's motto was "Glory to God, Peace on Earth, Kindness, Justice and Mercy to Every Living Creature".
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-education-society] On its establishment, AHES membership categories included life memberships and annual memberships at different fee levels.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-education-society] The AHES worked in partnership with the MSPCA, and *Our Dumb Animals* served as an official publication of both organizations.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-education-society] The society promoted *Black Beauty* as a humane education text in the United States.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-education-society] It printed an American edition in 1890 and distributed large numbers, with Angell arguing that the book could reduce cruelty to horses.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-education-society] The AHES distributed pamphlets and other humane education texts.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-education-society] Its activities included poster and essay competitions, illustrated lectures, and advocacy for humane education in school curricula.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-education-society] Fieldworkers operated in the United States and in other countries, including Canada, Turkey, Greece, Switzerland, Holland, France, Mexico, and Cuba.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-education-society] In 1914, AHES began a "Be Kind to Animals" campaign, using promotional items such as a metal button.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-education-society] The MSPCA's historical timeline records the first national observance of "Be Kind to Animals Week" in 1915.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-education-society] In 1918, the AHES and MSPCA formed the Jack London Club in response to concerns about the use of animals in entertainment.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-education-society] Club members received copies of Jack London's novels *Jerry of the Islands* (1916) and *Michael, Brother of Jerry* (1917).
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-education-society] By the 1920s, the club had about 750,000 members.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-education-society] In 2010, the AHES was merged into MSPCA-Angell.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-education-society] In 2012, the National Museum of Animals & Society launched the online exhibition "Be Kind: A Visual History of Humane Education, 1880-1945", curated by Keri Cronin.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-education-society] The exhibition includes a section on the AHES and reproduces selected material associated with its work, including circulars, brochures, posters, and campaign ephemera from the MSPCA-Angell collections.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] The **American Humane Society** (previously **American Humane**), is an American animal welfare organization founded in 1877 committed to ensuring the safety, welfare, and well-being of animals.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] It was previously called the **International Humane Association** and subsequently the **American Humane Association** and American Humane before changing its name to American Humane Society in 2025.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] In 1940, it became the sole monitoring body for the humane treatment of animals on the sets of unionized Hollywood films and other broadcast productions, a role it maintains through an agreement with the Screen Actors Guild.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] American Humane Society is best known for its certification mark "No Animals Were Harmed", which appears at the end of film or television credits where animals are featured.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] The organization also rescues animals following natural disasters, and runs programs that certify farms, zoos, and aquariums, among other institutions for the humane treatment of animals.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] American Humane Society is headquartered in Washington, D.C.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] It is a section 501(c)(3) nonprofit organization.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] American Humane Society began on October 9, 1877, as the International Humane Association, with the amalgamation of 27 organizations from across the United States after a meeting at the Kennard House in Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] The invitation to the other groups came from the Illinois Humane Society, sent on September 15, 1877, to discuss the specific problem of farm animal maltreatment during their transport between the eastern and western US.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] Groups attending the meeting included associations from the State of New York, Illinois, Ohio, Pennsylvania, Michigan, Maryland, Connecticut, and New Hampshire.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] A group from Minnesota also pledged its support to the forthcoming results of the conference, though they could not attend, and a group from the Canadian province of Quebec requested that a transcript of the proceedings be sent to them afterward.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] The International Humane Association changed its name to the "American Humane Association" in November 1878.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] New member organizations were in attendance for their second annual general meeting, held in Baltimore, Maryland, and also came from California, Massachusetts, Maine, Delaware, and the District of Columbia.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] Canadian regions were also included in the Association.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] Rowley was Secretary of the American Humane Association.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] In 1916, American Humane Society founded Red Star Rescue Relief after the U.S.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] Secretary of War asked the organization to rescue injured horses on the battlefields of World War I.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] Officers in 1917 included President William O.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] Stillman and 2nd Vice-President Peter G.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] There were 36 Vice-Presidents listed including William Howard Taft, Thomas R.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] American Humane Society began its work in film in 1940 after an incident that occurred on the set of the film *Jesse James*.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] The group began protesting the public release of the film because of a scene in which a horse was forced to run off the edge of a cliff.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] The horse fell over 70 feet to the ground below and broke its spine, having to be put down afterwards.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] In 1966, American Humane Society's access to some sets was diminished for 14 years following the dismantling of the Hays Office, during which time their jurisdiction was lessened.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] In 1954, tensions within the ranks of American Humane Society members came to a head at the organization's annual meeting, as a member-nominated slate of board candidates stood for office in opposition to a board-nominated slate.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] The majority of those assembled at the Atlanta, Georgia convention elected the three candidates on the member-nominated slate; J.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] Perry, Raymond Naramore, and Roland Smith.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] In the meeting's aftermath, there were firings and resignations on the part of staff members, including Larry Andrews, Marcia Glaser, Helen Jones, and Fred Myers.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] This core group went on to found a new organization, the National Humane Society, later known as The Humane Society of the United States, as an alternative to American Humane Society.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] American Humane Society's first "No Animals Were Harmed" end credit was issued at the end of the movie *The Doberman Gang* in 1972.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] Since then, the group has launched programs to certify the humane treatment of animals at a wide variety of institutions.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] In 2000, the American Humane Certified Farm program created the first farm animal welfare label to be overseen by the U.S.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] The program began as "Free Farmed" under Adele Douglass and is now referred to as the American Humane Certified Farm Program.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] In 2025, the organization changed its name to "American Humane Society".
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] The American Humane Society's No Animals Were Harmed certification program oversees animals used during unionized media productions, and it is sanctioned by the Screen Actors Guild to oversee a production's humane care of animals.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] It is the only organization with jurisdiction to do so within the United States.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] Because of this, the society may choose to issue the end credit disclaimer "No Animals Were Harmed", with a piece of a filmstrip that depicts a dog, a horse and an elephant.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] American Humane Society also reports on animal safety during filming if public concerns arise or if animal accidents happen on the set.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] American Humane Society protects the animals on the set as well as the cast/crew members who interact with the animals.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] The society's standard of animal care was established in 1988 and continues to evolve.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] On the set, representatives attempt to ensure the guidelines are upheld.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] American Humane Society's oversight includes film, television, commercials, music videos, and internet productions.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] The Screen Actors Guild – and thus the American Humane Society – have no jurisdiction concerning non-American and non-union productions.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] In 2024, American Humane Society reported supervising 1,000 productions in 25 countries, protecting 100,000 animal actors.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] It's possible to see and search for the certification of a past film production or currently-released film productions through their Humane Hollywood website.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] •Full Certification: American Humane's Safety Representatives were on set to ensure the safety of the animals throughout production.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] •Modified Certification: American Humane's Safety Representatives were not able to monitor every scene in which animals appeared.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] However, American Humane oversaw significant animal action filmed in compliance with American Humane's Guidelines for the Safe Use of Animals in Filmed Media.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] After screening the finished product and cross-checking all animal action supervised during production, American Humane acknowledges that the filmmakers have cooperated fully with their process.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] •Special Circumstances: The current definition of this is unknown and is only described as special circumstances.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] Previously, in the former rating system, it was given when productions followed guidelines and there was cooperation with representatives, and yet, an incident occurred (injury, death, etc.) and it was determined the production or animal suppliers had no negligence or malice.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] The previous ratings system that was used had the following ratings: Outstanding, Acceptable, Special Circumstances, Unacceptable, Production Compliant, and Not Monitored.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] American Humane Society certifies farms after evaluating them in five criteria.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] The animals are expected to be free from hunger, discomfort, pain, and fear, and able to express normal behaviors.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] Farms that meet these criteria receive an American Humane Certified label.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] As of 2024, the American Humane Society reported that its farm program certifies nearly 200 producers and processors, represents 90 percent of cage-free-eggs sold in the U.S., and covers more than one billion farm animals.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] The American Humane Society also certifies zoos, aquariums, and conservation parks for the humane treatment of animals.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] The benchmarks in which facilities are judged are developed by the organization's Scientific Advisory Committee.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] As of 2024, the American Humane Society certifies 85 zoos, aquariums, and conservation parks across 17 countries.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] Each year a dog is awarded the Hero Dog Award, an accolade given to dogs that have contributed substantially to human society.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] There are several categories in which dogs can be nominated, including the Military Dog category.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] The grand prize for the American Hero Dog was previously reported to be $10,000, which is given to a charity that reflects the contributions of the animal.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] In 2011 and 2012 the awards were broadcast on the Hallmark Channel.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] The first winner of the national award was a dog named Roselle, who led his blind owner down from the 78th floor of the World Trade Center during the September 11 attacks.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] There were more than 400,000 votes cast in the online poll that determined the winner.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] Roselle died several months before the winner was announced.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] The award was given on November 11, 2011.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] According to *The Gettysburg Times*, the "American Humane Association began offering animal relief in August 1916, by accepting an invitation of the War Department to help animals used by the U.S.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] The invitation resulted in the development of the American Red Star Animal Relief Program later known as Red Star Rescue Relief.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] American Humane Society have units stationed across the country to rescue animals in crisis.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] It includes emergency response vehicles customized to help animals in disasters, as well as rescue equipment designed for animal search and rescue.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] American Humane Society previously managed initiatives to improve child welfare services.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] The Front Porch Project was launched in 1997 to prevent child abuse and neglect.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] Meanwhile, the Fatherhood Initiative helped to develop better methods of engaging non-resident fathers with children who are in the welfare system.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] American Humane Society operates a program that reunites retired military working dogs with their former handlers.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] American Humane Society pays to transport the dogs to the former handlers and covers veterinary care for the dogs for the remainder of their lives.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] This program was formalized in 2021, when American Humane Society created an official Military Working Dog Reunification Fund.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] American Humane Society operates the Pups4Patriots program, which connects veterans and first responders suffering from Post-Traumatic Stress and Traumatic Brain Injury with service dogs.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] American Humane Society pays the associated training and adoption costs for the veteran and first responder recipients of the program.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] The program has provided approximately 300 dogs to veterans and first responders in total.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] Global Humane Society is the international brand of American Humane Society.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] Global Humane Society has a certification program for international zoos, aquariums, and tourism destinations.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] Global Humane Society awards the annual Wolfgang Kiessling International Prize for Species Conservation to someone who makes a significant contribution to conservation.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] The group also oversees a nature preserve in South Africa, where it operates a rewilding program.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] Prior to 2025, Global Humane Society was known as Global Humane.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] American Humane Society's budget for 2024 was just over $65 million.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] Their total revenue during that same year was $68.5 million.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] The organization closed its Denver, Colorado office in 2011 and moved its operations to Washington, D.C.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] Previous board chair, Eric Bruner, resigned in January 2013 amidst revelations that American Humane Society paid $233,863 to his business partner, Gregory Dew, for unspecified consulting services.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] Dew was the highest paid American Humane "independent contractor" in the fiscal year that ended June 30, 2011, according to filings the charity submitted to the IRS.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] Other organization staff include program leaders that oversee the operations of initiatives ranging from No Animals Were Harmed to zoo and aquarium certifications.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] In the late 1980s, American Humane Society was accused by Bob Barker and the United Activists for Animal Rights of condoning animal cruelty on the set of *Project X* and in several other media projects.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] The basis of the accusation was the allowing of a cattle prod and a gun on set, and the rumored beating of the chimpanzee on set.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] American Humane Society responded by launching a $10 million suit for libel, slander and invasion of privacy against Barker.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] American Humane Society claimed that there had been a two-year "vendetta" against them behind the accusations.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] In a series of public advertisements along with the $10 million libel suit, American Humane Society stated that the allegations were made based on insufficient and misleading information.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] The suit was eventually settled by Barker's insurance company, which paid American Humane Society $300,000.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] In late 2013, *The Hollywood Reporter* ran a story which implicated American Humane Society in turning a blind eye to and underreporting incidents of animal abuse on television and movie sets.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] For example, during the filming of *The Hobbit: An Unexpected Journey*, 27 animals died.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] Nevertheless, the movie received a "No Animals Were Harmed" disclaimer.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] During the filming of the movie *Life of Pi*, the tiger "King" nearly drowned in a pool, yet this incident was not reported outside of the American Humane Society organization.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] In early 2017, CNN reported that American Humane Society's representative for the movie *A Dog's Purpose* failed to properly monitor and protect a dog used in the film.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] American Humane Society placed an employee on leave after a video was published showing the dog in distress while performing a stunt for the movie.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] The American Humane Society published *The National Humane Review* beginning in 1913.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] From 1976 to 1978, the publication appeared under the title *American Humane Magazine*.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] It was issued quarterly by the organization's Animal Protection Division.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-humane-society] The society publishes an annual report and newsletter.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The **American Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals** (**ASPCA**) is a non-profit organization dedicated to preventing animal cruelty.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] It is the oldest animal welfare organization in the United States.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] On February 8, 1866, Bergh pleaded on behalf of animals at a meeting at Clinton Hall in New York City.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] Some of the issues he discussed were cockfighting and the horrors of slaughterhouses.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] After getting signatures for his "Declaration of the Rights of Animals," Bergh was given an official charter to incorporate the ASPCA on April 10, 1866.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] On April 19, 1866, the first anti-cruelty law was passed in NY since the founding of ASPCA, and the organization was granted the right to enforce anti-cruelty laws.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 1867, ASPCA operated its first ambulance for injured horses and began advocating for more humane treatment of animals such as horses, live pigeons, cats, and dogs.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] Early goals of ASPCA focused on efforts for horses and livestock, since at the time they were used for a number of activities.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 1918, ASPCA veterinarians developed the use of anesthesia and as a result were able to work on a horse with a broken kneecap.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 1954, ASPCA hospitals added pathology and radiography laboratories and programs.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 1961, ASPCA veterinarians performed their first open-heart surgery on a dog.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] From 1894 to 1994, the ASPCA operated the municipal animal shelter system in New York City which euthanized unadopted animals.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] Starting in 1977, the ASPCA entered into a contract with the New York City Department of Health to receive municipal funding to operate the shelter system.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The contract rendered the ASPCA increasingly reliant on government income rather than private donations, and subject to the effects of annual city budget appropriations.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 1993, the ASPCA decided not to renew its contract for operating the shelter system.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] Operation of the shelter system was transferred to Center for Animal Care and Control, later renamed Animal Care Centers of NYC, in 1995.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 1996, ASPCA acquired the Animal Poison Control Center from the University of Illinois.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 2013, the ASPCA made a $25 million commitment to assist at-risk animals and pet owners in the greater Los Angeles metropolitan area, including a fully subsidized spay/neuter facility in South Los Angeles operated by the ASPCA and a campaign to encourage the fostering of local vulnerable kittens.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 2014, ASPCA spoke out in support of New York City's new mayor's (Bill de Blasio) campaign to ban horse-drawn carriages in the city.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 2014, ASPCA opened the Gloria Gurney Canine Annex for Recovery & Enrichment (CARE) in NYC to house dogs brought by the NYPD to the ASPCA in connection with animal cruelty investigations.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 2014, ASPCA also opened the ASPCA Kitten Nursery in NYC to care for neonate and very young homeless kittens until they are appropriate for adoption.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 2015, ASPCA acquired the Asheville, North Carolina–based Humane Alliance, now called the ASPCA Spay/Neuter Alliance.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 2018, ASPCA established the ASPCA Behavioral Rehabilitation Center.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] Located in Weaverville, North Carolina, the Center provides behavioral rehabilitation to canine victims of cruelty and neglect.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The center's Learning Lab also disseminates rehabilitative aid and training to shelters around the country.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 2019, ASPCA opened the ASPCA Community Veterinary Center in Liberty City, Miami, Florida, to provide subsidized veterinary services for an underserved community.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] It also took over responsibility for The Right Horse Initiative as an official program of the ASPCA in 2019.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 2020, ASPCA opened the ASPCA Community Veterinary Center in the Bronx, New York.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 2021, the Society opened the ASPCA Community Veterinary Center supported by the Alex and Elisabeth Lewyt Charitable Trust, in NYC.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] As of 2023, ASPCA's New York hospital was treating 9,000–10,000 patients annually.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 2023, ASPCA began releasing an annual report that grades major grocery retailers in the United States on their policies around animal welfare, such as selling cage-free eggs and pork raised without gestation crates.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] An ASPCA fundraising commercial featuring Sarah McLachlan began airing in early 2007.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] By December 2008, it had raised more than $30 million for the ASPCA, becoming the organization's most successful fundraising campaign.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The *New York Times* reported that the spot became known as "The Ad" in non-profit circles.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 2021, CBS News reported that the ad misled donors, who believed that their financial contributions supported local SPCAs and animal welfare charities.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The CBS News investigation focused on "questions about whether the money is going where donors expect," reporting the ASPCA raised $2 billion for animal welfare between 2008 and 2019 and spent only $146 million in grants to local animal welfare groups.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In response, a spokesperson for the ASPCA said that donors were aware that the ASPCA was not an umbrella organization for local organizations with SPCA in their names.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] After the CBS News piece aired, two widely-shared posts on Facebook claimed that the ASPCA's CEO was paid $600,000 annually, and that only three cents of each dollar donated were used "for veterinary supplies and for transporting the animals".
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] *USA Today* fact-checked the posts and found that based on ASPCA tax filings, 34.4% of the ASPCA's budget was used for shelter and veterinary care, and an average of 75.1% of expenses were used to support its mission statement.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 2012, the ASPCA agreed to pay Ringling Bros. and Barnum & Bailey Circus $9.3 million to settle a lawsuit regarding the ASPCA's false allegations of animal cruelty by the circus.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] Courts found that ASPCA activists had paid the key witness, a former Ringling barn helper, at least $190,000, making him "essentially a paid plaintiff" who lacked credibility.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] Sayres stepped down as CEO in 2012, and in 2013 longtime ASPCA staff member Matthew Bershadker was named president and CEO.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The ASPCA's Government Relations, Legal Advocacy and Investigations departments work with state and federal lawmakers and engage in legislative and litigation efforts to secure stronger legal protections for animals.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] Some of the animal welfare issues the departments work on include ending puppy mills and breed-specific legislation.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] Department of Agriculture for access to animal breeder inspection records.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The filed lawsuit claimed that Defendants-Appellees the U.S.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] ASPCA was among the animal welfare groups that supported the "puppy mill pipeline" bill in New York, which was signed by Governor Kathy Hochul on December 15, 2022.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The law went into effect in 2024 and makes it illegal to sell dogs, cats, and rabbits in pet stores in New York.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The organization's senior director of state legislation said the law is needed because many puppies are imported from other states where New York does not have jurisdiction to inspect the conditions in the breeding facility.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] At the invitation of local agencies, ASPCA deploys to sites of large-scale animal abuse, animal neglect, natural disasters, or man-made disasters in which animals are at risk.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] Teams, including National Field Response, Legal Advocacy and Investigations, Forensic Sciences, the Cruelty Recovery Center, Relocation and the Behavioral Sciences team, engage in animal rescue efforts.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] They provide behavioral and medical treatment for the animals and support the prosecution of criminal cases with forensic science, evidence collection and analysis, and legal and expert testimony support.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] Cases involving torture, killings and mistreatment of animals are some examples of cases handled by the ASPCA.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] A common example was displayed in the news in October 2008, when ASPCA was in charge of an investigation involving the slaughtering of a beagle that lived in the Bronx.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 2016, ASPCA field deployment teams participated in a large animal cruelty rescue operation, rescuing nearly 700 animals from an unlicensed facility in North Carolina.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In September 2013, after many years of providing humane law enforcement services in NYC, the ASPCA and the New York City Police Department announced a collaboration to provide enhanced protection to New York City's animals.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In this partnership, the NYPD responds to all animal cruelty complaints throughout New York City, while the ASPCA provides medical and behavioral care for animal cruelty victims and provides legal and forensic assistance in the prosecution of cases.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The ASPCA Community Engagement team also works closely with the NYPD to connect pets in need to services such as medical care, grooming and pet supplies.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 2020, ASPCA also opened the ASPCA Veterinary Forensic Science Center in Gainesville, Florida, to assist law enforcement with animal cruelty investigations and prosecutions.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] Between 2010 and 2025, ASPCA helped investigate 300 dogfighting cases that resulted in the rescue of 6,000 dogs.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 2013, ASPCA cared for 367 dogs that were rescued from Alabama, Mississippi, Georgia and Texas from what was the second largest dogfighting ring in the United States to date.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The organization sheltered the dogs in an air conditioned, converted warehouse, providing medical and behavioral rehabilitation.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] Alabama Media Group reported that none of the dogs had to be euthanized.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The organization partnered with the National Museum of Crime and Punishment to provide items for an exhibit on dogfighting in 2013.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] ASPCA worked with the Kansas Bureau of Investigation in 2018 to rescue 45 dogs and nine puppies from a dogfighting ring in Bendena, Kansas.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The investigation also included the organization uncovering dogfighting paraphernalia, like treadmills and chains.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 2025, ASPCA partnered with the State of South Carolina to prosecute dogfighting rings and issued 15 related search warrants.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In March of that year, it sheltered and cared for 28 dogs rescued from a single dogfighting ring in Luzerne County.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] Following natural disasters, ASPCA provides on the ground assistance providing displaced animals food and shelter.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] It also provides grants for other organizations to invest in climate-related disaster preparedness, such as purchasing emergency supplies, power generators, and animal transport units.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] ASPCA reported assisting at least 550 animals following Hurricane Florence.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] After a Hurricane in Monroe County, Mississippi, the organization partnered with local human societies and Mississippi State University's veterinary program to relocate and give animals medical checks.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 2024, after Hurricane Helene its disaster response team provided pet supplies, medication, and veterinary support to affected communities in Florida, Georgia, and North Carolina.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] ASPCA partnered with a Texas-based animal response team to evacuate over 100 displaced animals after storm-related flooding damaged a shelter at Pilot Point, Texas.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] It provided shelter as well as medical and behavioral care for the animals.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] Following the 2025 California wildfires, ASPCA announced a $5 million dollar fund for animal welfare organizations in Los Angeles county.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The ASPCA's Right Horse Initiative is focused on increasing the number of successful horse adoptions in the U.S. and improving the number of positive outcomes for horses in transition as they move from one home, career, or owner to the next.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] ASPCA works with other animal welfare organizations and rescue groups to relocate animals from areas with high rates of euthanasia in animal shelters to locations with higher adoption rates.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] Often, animals are moved from the southern to northern U.S. states.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] Animals may be transported using aircraft or vehicles, sometimes being relayed between transporters multiple times along the way.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] As of March 2022, ASPCA had a fleet of 18 vans used for transport.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The organization relocated approximately 200,000 animals between 2017 and 2022.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] ASPCA operates centers where dogs that have experienced abuse or trauma receive treatment and behavior rehabilitation before being cleared for adoption.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] As of 2022, the organization has committed $40 million to building and operating the centers, which are located in Weaverville, North Carolina, Columbus, Ohio, with another being developed in Pawling, New York.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The Weaverville center opened in 2020 and was the world's first clinic for treating dogs that have been severely traumatized.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The concept was conceived in 2010 by two ASPCA behaviorists as a way to reduce the number of dogs that are euthanized in shelters for behavior issues.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The organization piloted the program in 2013 at a temporary site in Madison, New Jersey and reported that approximately 90 percent of the dogs treated recovered enough to be adopted.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 2014, ASPCA purchased land in Weaverville where it built the center.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] As of July 2022, the Weaverville center had 35 full-time staff, and had rehabilitated 500 dogs since opening.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The ASPCA published *The Animal Kingdom* magazine in the 1870s which became *Our Animal Friends: An Illustrated Monthly Magazine* in the 1890s.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The magazine featured articles from well known authors of the day, including Louisa May Alcott and Harriet Beecher Stowe.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] It was renamed *Animal Protection* (1947–1977) and later became *ASPCA Bulletin* (1977–1981), *ASPCA Quarterly Report* (1981–1989), *ASPCA Report* (1989–1992) and *Animal Watch: The Magazine of the American Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals* (1993–2004).
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] In 1964, Lloyd Alexander authored their history, *Fifty Years in the Doghouse* which was commissioned by the ASPCA.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] Copies of the ASPCA's magazine *Animal Protection* are digitized and stored at NC State University Libraries.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/american-society-for-the-prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals] The ASPCA currently publishes the *ASPCA Action* magazine.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/an-essay-on-humanity-to-animals] Thomas Young was educated at Trinity College, Cambridge, where he matriculated in 1790 and graduated as 12th Wrangler in 1794.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/an-essay-on-humanity-to-animals] He later became a fellow of the college, and served as a tutor and senior dean.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/an-essay-on-humanity-to-animals] In 1813, he was appointed rector of Gilling East, Yorkshire, a post he held until his death in 1835.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/an-essay-on-humanity-to-animals] The book was published on 9 March 1798 by T.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/an-essay-on-humanity-to-animals] Davies in the Strand, London, with additional distribution by W.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/an-essay-on-humanity-to-animals] An abridged edition was published in 1804 by Knott and Lloyd in Birmingham.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/an-essay-on-humanity-to-animals] In 2001, an edited edition prepared by Rod Preece was published by Edwin Mellen Press.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/an-essay-on-humanity-to-animals] It included an introduction and annotations by Preece, with a foreword by David Fraser.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/an-essay-on-humanity-to-animals] The volume is prefixed by an "Ode to Humanity" by the Reverend C.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/an-essay-on-humanity-to-animals] Hoyle of Trinity College, Cambridge, written at Young's request.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/an-essay-on-humanity-to-animals] The main text is arranged in chapters dealing with different forms of cruelty to animals and with the duties humans owe them.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/an-essay-on-humanity-to-animals] Young argues at the outset that animals are capable of pleasure and pain, and that this capacity places them within the scope of moral concern.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/an-essay-on-humanity-to-animals] He links cruelty to animals with broader habits of violence and coarseness, and holds that humane treatment is required both by natural law and by Christian ethics.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/an-essay-on-humanity-to-animals] Several chapters attack forms of cruelty practised for entertainment.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/an-essay-on-humanity-to-animals] Young condemns blood sports such as bull-baiting and cockfighting, as well as hunting, shooting, and fishing for amusement.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/an-essay-on-humanity-to-animals] He also argues that children should be taught from an early age not to torment animals, since cruelty in youth may harden the character.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/an-essay-on-humanity-to-animals] Young also discusses everyday treatment of animals.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/an-essay-on-humanity-to-animals] He gives particular attention to horses, which he describes as useful and often badly used, and he criticises overwork, mutilation, and neglect.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/an-essay-on-humanity-to-animals] Elsewhere he objects to the confinement of wild animals for amusement and to cruel practices in food production, including the treatment of fish and bees.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/an-essay-on-humanity-to-animals] In the closing parts of the book he turns to dogs and other domestic animals, urging readers to repay their dependence and attachment with care rather than abuse.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/an-essay-on-humanity-to-animals] In a chapter in *The Oxford Handbook of Animal Ethics*, Aaron Garrett places Young's book alongside works by writers such as John Lawrence as part of a move toward more practical arguments for animal protection, connected with wider reform movements of the period.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/an-essay-on-humanity-to-animals] Salt listed *An Essay on Humanity to Animals* in the bibliography of *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress*.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/an-essay-on-humanity-to-animals] Benjamin Bryan quoted from it in *Anti-Vivisection Evidences* (1895), and Edward Payson Evans included it in the bibliography of *Evolutional Ethics and Animal Psychology* (1898).
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/an-essay-on-humanity-to-animals] Magel listed it in *Keyguide to Information Sources in Animal Rights*.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/an-essay-on-humanity-to-animals] According to Rod Preece, John Styles's *The Animal Creation: Its Claims on Our Humanity Stated and Enforced* appears to have drawn heavily on Young's earlier writings.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/an-essay-on-humanity-to-animals] Preece also compares Young with church writers on animal treatment such as Richard Dean and Humphrey Primatt.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/an-essay-on-humanity-to-animals] In 2013, the American Philosophical Society Library included Young's work in a web exhibit on the history of animal studies.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-aid-unlimited] Animal Aid Unlimited opened the Animal Aid Hospital in 2002.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-aid-unlimited] As of 2017, the organization claims to have saved more than 45,000 injured or ill dogs, cows, donkeys, birds and cats.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-aid-unlimited] In 2021, Gary Notely, a dog training instructor, hosted a charity event at Zara Indian Restaurant in Woodham Mortimer.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-aid-unlimited] On 26 April 2017, Bollywood actress Anushka Sharma, who is also an animal welfare activist and an avid animal lover, made a surprise visit to the shelter.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-aid-unlimited] Its rescue videos are also frequently featured in the social media platforms of The Dodo.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-aid-unlimited] As of January 2025, their YouTube channel has over 7.34 million subscribers.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-aid-unlimited] Some of the most viral videos of the channel are "*Wounded and bleeding donkey stranded on highway rescued*", " *Anguished mother dog wails for wounded baby.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-aid-unlimited] Sweetest reunion!*" & "*A drowning dog's desperate wish comes true*" all of which have 173; 145 and 121 million views respectively.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The **Animal Defence and Anti-Vivisection Society** (**ADAVS**), also known as the **Animal Defence Society** was an animal welfare organisation, co-founded in England, in 1906, by Lizzy Lind af Hageby, and Nina Douglas-Hamilton, Duchess of Hamilton.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The objective of the Society was a "Consistent Opposition to all forms of Cruelty to Animals and Abolition of Vivisection".
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The Society was known for its support of humane slaughter.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The Society's assets were transferred to a charity, The Animal Defence Trust that was registered in 1971.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] It was based for many years at Animal Defence House, 15 St James's Place, London, and ran a 237-acre animal sanctuary at Ferne House near Shaftesbury, Dorset, an estate owned by the Duke and Duchess of Hamilton.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] An early member of the Society's executive council was Alice Drakoules who was a lifelong campaigner for animal welfare and a keen supporter of the Society.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] She helped the Society campaign for humane slaughter, licensed slaughterhouses and for an end to performing animals.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The Society came to widespread attention during the Brown Dog affair (1903–1910), which began when Lind af Hageby infiltrated the vivisection in University College London of a brown terrier dog.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The subsequent description of the experiment in her book, *The Shambles of Science* (1903) – in which she wrote that the dog had been conscious throughout and in pain – led to a protracted scandal and a libel case, which the accused researcher won.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The affair continued for several years, making a name both for Lind af Hageby and for the Society.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The Society was associated with Hageby's International Humanitarian Bureau.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] It published *The Anti-Vivisection and Humanitarian Review* in 1929 and *Progress Today: The Humanitarian and Anti-Vivisection Review* in the 1930s.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] In 1933, members of the Society's executive council included Sara Blomfield, Charlotte Despard, Douglas S.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] In 1959, the Society protested against a mass pigeon shoot throughout the East of England the Midlands.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] Despite supporting total abolition of vivisection the Society advocated reform of animal slaughter.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The Society called for legislation making humane slaughter compulsory.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The Society advertised its own "humane killer" for sale, a type of captive bolt pistol.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] In 1923, the Society advocated a statement of minimum slaughter reform that was sent to the Cabinet Committee.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] Their proposal was that local authorities should be under obligation to approve only types of human killers for use in the slaughterhouse within their districts and that inspectors should be allowed to enter the slaughterhouse to enforce the Act.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] They urged that all slaughtermen should be licensed and that any other method of killing animals for food should be prohibited.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The Society opposed the use of the knife and poleaxe in slaughter.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] Lizzy Lind af Hageby and Duchess Nina Douglas-Hamilton both visited slaughterhouses and tested the "humane killer" and criticized the cruelty of the poleaxe.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] In 1924, a report they signed had found that a pig had to be hit four times on the head before it was rendered unconscious and that the humane killer rendered twenty animals unconscious by the first shot.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] In 1925, it was reported that the Duchess of Hamilton had witnessed 52 animals being slaughtered in a single afternoon in pursuance of the statutory use of the humane killer.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The Society supported the Slaughter of Animals Act 1933.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The humane killer gained support from slaughterhouse workers.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] John Dodds, superintendent of the Carlisle abattoir became an expert adviser to the Society in their campaign for compulsory use of the humane killer.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The Society's Slaughter Reform Department consisted of John Dodds and Constance Warner.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] In 1937, the Society organized an exhibition in London with demonstrations of humane killers.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] In 1939, the Society angered the poultry industry by campaigning against the use of battery cage hens.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The Society stated that the hens are imprisoned in the battery system in a confined space with no contact with fresh air and grass.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The Society campaigned for the abolition of private slaughterhouses and the creation of humanely-conducted public abattoirs.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] In 1929, the Society opened the "Model Humane Abattoir" in Letchworth.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The building was owned by the Society and was used to demonstrate humane slaughter and hygienic treatment of meat.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The humane model abattoir was built on a site covering two acres and planned to deal with 20,000 animals a year.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The site contained a slaughter hall, lairs, cooling hall for cattle, general loading stage, chill rooms, engine room, a large lecture theatre and a veterinary inspection area.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The Society also planned to build a bacon factory in which pigs were shot with the humane killer.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The model humane abattoir gained support from the National Council for Animals' Welfare.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The Society stated that meat from the abattoir was to be sold by their own company.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] Duchess Nina Douglas-Hamilton was a vegetarian in her personal life but in 1928 became the head of a humane butcher's shop.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] Following Lind af Hageby's death in December 1963, the Society's assets were transferred to a trust, The Animal Defence Trust, which continues to offer grants for animal-protection projects.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The Animal Defence Trust registered as a charity in 1971.
[src:a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] NC State University Libraries holds a large collection of pamphlets from the Animal Defence and Anti-Vivisection Society.
